4B. Transport Protocol % of TCP and UDP Packets¶

From:

  • https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_IP_protocol_numbers

Meanings:

  • 6 -> TCP protocol
  • 17 -> UDP protocol
In [4]:
transport_protocol_group = data.groupby(['IP_protocol']).size().reset_index(name='# of times')
sorted_transport_protocol_data = transport_protocol_group.sort_values(by=['# of times'], ascending=False).set_index(['IP_protocol'])

In [5]:
total_numbers_of_packets = len(data.index)
tcp_packets = 879
udp_packets = 135

percentage_of_tcp_packets = (tcp_packets / total_numbers_of_packets) * 100
percentage_of_udp_packets = (udp_packets / total_numbers_of_packets) * 100

print(f"TCP Packet Percentage = {percentage_of_tcp_packets}%")
print(f"UDP Packet Percentage = {percentage_of_udp_packets}%")

TCP Packet Percentage = 73.25%
UDP Packet Percentage = 11.25%

4C. Application Protocol¶

From:

  • https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_TCP_and_UDP_port_numbers
  • http://www.adminsub.net/tcp-udp-port-finder/56152

Meanings:

  • 0 -> In programming APIs (not in communication between hosts), requests a system-allocated (dynamic) port
  • 80 -> Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP)
  • 443 -> Hypertext Transfer Protocol over TLS/SSL (HTTPS)
  • 43930 -> Unassigned
  • 56152 -> Dynamic and/or Private Ports. Xsan. Xsan Filesystem Access
In [6]:
app_protocol_group = data.groupby(['udp/tcp_dst_port']).size().reset_index(name='# of times')
sorted_app_protocol_data = app_protocol_group.sort_values(by=['# of times'], ascending=False).set_index(['udp/tcp_dst_port'])

4D. Traffic Intensity¶

In [7]:
packet_size_data = data['IP_size']
total_traffic_in_bytes = packet_size_data.sum()
total_traffic_in_Megabytes = total_traffic_in_bytes / 1000**2
print(f"Total Traffic (MB) = {total_traffic_in_Megabytes} MB")

Total Traffic (MB) = 1.079883 MB

4E. Additional Analysis : Most active + Least active of inputPorts and outputPorts¶

We can determine if the usage of port by routher is well balanced. If not, could consider carrying out balancing of ports at router

In [10]:
from IPython.core.display import display, HTML

def display_side_by_side(dfs:list, captions:list):
    """Display tables side by side to save vertical space
    Input:
        dfs: list of pandas.DataFrame
        captions: list of table captions
    """
    output = ""
    combined = dict(zip(captions, dfs))
    for caption, df in combined.items():
        output += df.style.set_table_attributes("style='display:inline'").set_caption(caption)._repr_html_()
        output += "\xa0\xa0\xa0"
    display(HTML(output))

input_ports_group = data.groupby(['inputPort']).size().reset_index(name="# of times port is used")
sorted_input_ports = input_ports_group.sort_values(by=['# of times port is used']).set_index(['inputPort'])

output_ports_group = data.groupby(['outputPort']).size().reset_index(name="# of times port is used")
sorted_output_ports = output_ports_group.sort_values(by=['# of times port is used']).set_index(['outputPort'])

port_pairs_group = data.groupby(['inputPort', 'outputPort']).size().reset_index(name='# of times input and output pair is used')
sorted_duplex_ports = port_pairs_group.sort_values(by=['# of times input and output pair is used']).reset_index().drop('index', axis=1)

display_side_by_side([sorted_input_ports, sorted_output_ports, sorted_duplex_ports], ['inputPorts','outputPorts', 'portPairs'])
